name: undecane
source: American Petroleum Institute. Research Project 44; Selected Values of Properties of Hydrocarbons and Related Compounds. Texas A & M University; College Station; TX; 1973.
Reason: The structural formula of undecane is a straight chain of 11 carbon atoms with 22 hydrogen atoms (C11H24). The reference compound, n-pentane, which has a similar straight-chain structure with 5 carbon atoms (C5H12), has a melting point of -130°C. Each additional CH2 group in a straight-chain alkane can be seen to increase the melting point by approximately 20°C due to the increased surface area and van der Waals forces. n-Pentane plus 6 CH2 groups (to make undecane) would give an increase of approximately 6 x 20°C = 120°C. Thus, melting point of undecane is expected to be -130°C + 120°C.

Reason: The structural formula of undecane is a straight chain of 11 carbon atoms with 22 hydrogen atoms (C11H24). However, each additional CH2 group in a straight-chain alkane increases the melting point by a lesser amount than mentioned, approximately 5°C due to the incremental increase in van der Waals interactions and surface area. Therefore, with undecane having 6 more CH2 groups than n-pentane, we can expect an increase of 6 x 5°C = 30°C. Thus, the predicted melting point of undecane is -130°C + 30°C.

name: undecane
source: American Petroleum Institute. Research Project 44; Selected Values of Properties of Hydrocarbons and Related Compounds. Texas A & M University; College Station; TX; 1973.
Reason: The basic unit for considering melting points in hydrocarbons is methane, which has a melting point of -182°C. Each additional CH2 group in a hydrocarbon chain generally increases the melting point because of the increase in van der Waals forces as the carbon chain gets longer. In the case of undecane, which is a chain of 11 carbon atoms, we can make a rough estimate of the melting point increase per CH2 group and add that incrementally. For normal alkanes, the addition of each CH2 group can raise the melting point by about +5°C from methane. Undecane has 10 more CH2 groups than methane, so we predict an increment of 10 x 5°C = 50°C from methane's melting point.
